data.content:
This is a **timeout enforcement** pattern. `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8 (SYSLIB0006). Here's the full migration:

## What's Wrong in .NET 8

| API | Problem |
|-----|---------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never fires — the exception type still exists but is never thrown |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Preferred: async overload
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout, CancellationToken token = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(token);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await Task.Run(work, cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        // If token (caller's) was cancelled, OperationCanceledException propagates as-is
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|----------------|
| **Cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive** | If `work` is a CPU-bound loop that never checks a token, it keeps running even after the timeout. `WaitAsync` lets the *caller* stop waiting, but the abandoned `Task.Run` continues on a thread-pool thread until it finishes naturally. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers. Always `using`. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish timeout from caller cancellation. |
| **Blocking on async code** | The sync overload uses `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` — safe here since `Task.Run` avoids `SynchronizationContext` capture, but prefer the async overload. |

## If `work` Must Be Truly Cancellable

Accept a `CancellationToken` in the work delegate so it can cooperate:

```csharp
public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
    Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout,
    CancellationToken token = default)
{
    using var cts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(token);
    cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

    try
    {
        return await Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token)
                         .WaitAsync(cts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Usage — the work checks the token:
var result = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(ct =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return "done";
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

## If Work Is Truly Uncooperative (e.g., third-party code)

Move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()` — this is the only reliable way to forcibly stop code that can't check a token. `Task.Run` with an abandoned task is acceptable for fire-and-forget scenarios but the thread-pool thread is not reclaimed until the work completes.
